# Useful Investigation Tips

* Always verify suspicious parent-child process relationships
* Check unusual PowerShell activity
* Investigate unknown network connections
* Compare pslist and psscan results
* Dump suspicious processes for malware analysis
* Use VirusTotal on dumped files
* Analyze persistence mechanisms

# Example Investigation Flow

```bash
volatility -f memory.img imageinfo

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 pslist

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 pstree

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 netscan

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 cmdline

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 malfind

volatility -f memory.img --profile=Win7SP1x64 procdump -p 1234 -D output/

# Key Points to Remember

* RAM contains volatile evidence
* Memory analysis helps detect fileless malware
* Volatility is the most commonly used tool
* pslist + psscan comparison is important
* netscan helps identify attacker communication
* malfind is useful for injected malware
* procdump extracts suspicious executables

# Conclusion
Memory Forensics is an essential skill in cybersecurity and incident response. It helps investigators analyze live memory to identify malicious activities, attacker behavior, malware, and system compromise evidence that may not exist on disk.

